    slug: "mary-gordon-dinsmoor",
    name: "Mary Gordon Dinsmoor | Dinsmore Farm Museum",
    shortBio: `Little is known of Mary Gordon’s childhood in Hampstead, New Hampshire. Since she was, for a short time, a student at Atkinson Academy where her future husband, Silas, taught in the early 1790s, she was likely born in the late 1770s. Her father, John Gordon, was a prosperous farmer and merchant, and a member of the New Hampshire legislature. Her mother, Mary (Little) Gordon, was the daughter of Colonel Moses Little, a Revolutionary War veteran and prominent citizen of Atkinson, New Hampshire. Mary Gordon was one of eight children, and the only daughter to survive to adulthood.`,
    fullBio: `Little is known of Mary Gordon’s childhood in Hampstead, New Hampshire. Since she was, for a short time, a student at Atkinson Academy where her future husband, Silas, taught in the early 1790s, she was likely born in the late 1770s. Her father, John Gordon, was a prosperous farmer and merchant, and a member of the New Hampshire legislature. Her mother, Mary (Little) Gordon, was the daughter of Colonel Moses Little, a Revolutionary War veteran and prominent citizen of Atkinson, New Hampshire. Mary Gordon was one of eight children, and the only daughter to survive to adulthood.
Mary Gordon married Silas Dinsmoor on May 1, 1804, in Atkinson, New Hampshire. Silas was a graduate of Dartmouth College and a teacher at Atkinson Academy. He later became a surveyor and land agent for the federal government, and served as a U.S. Indian Agent to the Cherokee Nation from 1802 to 1813. During their marriage, Mary and Silas had six children: Mary Gordon Dinsmoor (b. 1805), Silas Dinsmoor Jr. (b. 1807), John Gordon Dinsmoor (b. 1809), Elizabeth Little Dinsmoor (b. 1811), William Dinsmoor (b. 1813), and George Dinsmoor (b. 1815).
In 1813, Silas Dinsmoor was removed from his position as Indian Agent due to political disagreements. The family then moved to Kentucky, where Silas purchased a farm near Burlington in Boone County. Mary Gordon Dinsmoor managed the household and helped with the farm work. She was also responsible for the education of her children, as there were no public schools in the area at the time.
Mary Gordon Dinsmoor died on October 2, 1827, at the age of 49, and was buried in the Dinsmoor family cemetery on the farm. Silas Dinsmoor later remarried and had more children. The Dinsmoor farm remained in the family for several generations and is now a museum dedicated to preserving the history of the Dinsmoor family and their role in the development of Boone County.
Early Life and Family
Mary Gordon was born in Hampstead, New Hampshire, in the late 1770s. Her parents were John Gordon and Mary (Little) Gordon. John Gordon was a successful farmer and merchant who also served in the New Hampshire legislature. Mary (Little) Gordon was the daughter of Colonel Moses Little, a Revolutionary War veteran and a respected figure in Atkinson, New Hampshire. Mary Gordon was one of eight children, but she was the only daughter to survive to adulthood.
Mary Gordon received some education at Atkinson Academy, where her future husband, Silas Dinsmoor, was a teacher in the early 1790s. This early connection likely played a role in their eventual marriage.
Marriage and Life as an Indian Agent's Wife
On May 1, 1804, Mary Gordon married Silas Dinsmoor in Atkinson, New Hampshire. Silas was a man of considerable education, having graduated from Dartmouth College. Before their marriage, he had been a teacher and later became a surveyor and land agent for the federal government.
From 1802 to 1813, Silas Dinsmoor served as a U.S. Indian Agent to the Cherokee Nation. During this period, Mary Gordon Dinsmoor would have experienced life on the frontier, which presented unique challenges and opportunities. They had six children during their marriage:
Mary Gordon Dinsmoor (b. 1805)
Silas Dinsmoor Jr. (b. 1807)
John Gordon Dinsmoor (b. 1809)
Elizabeth Little Dinsmoor (b. 1811)
William Dinsmoor (b. 1813)
George Dinsmoor (b. 1815)
Move to Kentucky and Farm Life
In 1813, Silas Dinsmoor's tenure as an Indian Agent ended due to political disputes. The family subsequently relocated to Kentucky, where Silas purchased a farm near Burlington in Boone County. This marked a significant shift in their lives, moving from the diplomatic and administrative roles of an Indian Agent to the more agrarian lifestyle of a farmer.
Mary Gordon Dinsmoor took on the responsibilities of managing the household and actively participated in the farm work. In addition to her domestic and agricultural duties, she played a crucial role in the education of her children, as formal schooling options were scarce in the area at that time.
Later Years and Legacy
Mary Gordon Dinsmoor passed away on October 2, 1827, at the age of 49. She was laid to rest in the Dinsmoor family cemetery located on their farm. After her death, Silas Dinsmoor remarried and had more children.
The Dinsmoor farm remained a family possession for several generations. Today, it stands as a museum, dedicated to preserving the rich history of the Dinsmoor family and their significant contributions to the development of Boone County. Mary Gordon Dinsmoor's life, though perhaps less documented than her husband's, was integral to the family's journey and the establishment of their legacy in Kentucky.`,
